    <p>Plumbing problems are inevitable for any homeowner. Understanding common issues and their solutions can help you know when to tackle a problem yourself and when to call a professional.</p>

    <h2>Dripping Taps</h2>
    
    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>A single dripping tap can waste thousands of liters of water annually and increase water bills significantly.</p>
    
    <h3>Common Causes</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Worn washers (most common in older taps)</li>
        <li>Damaged valve seats</li>
        <li>Mineral buildup from hard water</li>
        <li>Loose packing nuts</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>DIY or Professional?</h3>
    <p>Simple tap repairs with new washers can be DIY projects, but modern tap repairs often require professional replacement of entire cartridges or mechanisms.</p>

    <h2>Clogged or Slow Drains</h2>

    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>Standing water in sinks, showers, or toilets indicates drainage issues.</p>

    <h3>Common Causes</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Hair accumulation in shower and bathroom drains</li>
        <li>Grease buildup in kitchen drains</li>
        <li>Soap scum and detergent residue</li>
        <li>Mineral deposits</li>
        <li>Tree roots in sewer lines</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Solutions</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Plunger (works for many clogs)</li>
        <li>Drain snake for deeper blockages</li>
        <li>Chemical drain cleaners (use caution - harmful)</li>
        <li>Professional drain cleaning and hydro-jetting</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Running Toilets</h2>

    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>Water continuously running in the toilet tank wastes significant water and increases bills.</p>

    <h3>Common Causes</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Worn flapper valve</li>
        <li>Float mechanism malfunction</li>
        <li>Dirty fill valve</li>
        <li>Cracks in the tank</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Solutions</h3>
    <p>Most running toilet issues can be fixed by replacing the flapper or fill valve - relatively simple DIY repairs or affordable professional repairs.</p>

    <h2>Leaking Pipes</h2>

    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>Water leaks waste water, increase bills, and can cause structural damage.</p>

    <h3>Common Causes</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Corrosion in old pipes</li>
        <li>Freezing (in cold areas)</li>
        <li>High water pressure</li>
        <li>Loose connections</li>
        <li>Physical damage</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Solutions</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Temporary pipe clamps or tape for emergency situations</li>
        <li>Professional repair or pipe replacement</li>
        <li>Pressure regulator installation to reduce strain</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Low Water Pressure</h2>

    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>Weak water flow makes showering and cleaning difficult.</p>

    <h3>Common Causes</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Mineral buildup on aerators</li>
        <li>Partially closed shut-off valves</li>
        <li>Leaks reducing pressure</li>
        <li>Municipal water supply issues</li>
        <li>Corrosion in old pipes</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Solutions</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Clean aerators (DIY)</li>
        <li>Check shut-off valve position (DIY)</li>
        <li>Pressure regulator adjustment</li>
        <li>Professional pipe cleaning or replacement</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Water Heater Issues</h2>

    <h3>Common Problems</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>No hot water</li>
        <li>Fluctuating water temperature</li>
        <li>Leaking tanks</li>
        <li>Strange noises</li>
        <li>Rusty water</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Solutions</h3>
    <p>Water heater repairs often require professional service. Many issues indicate the need for replacement rather than repair.</p>

